● **Part VIII of the Constitution of India** deals with the administration of Union Territories (UTs). These are the areas which are under the direct control and administration of the Central Government.
● Every UT is administered by the President acting through an administrator appointed by him. **An** **administrator of a Union Territory is an agent of the President and not head of state like a** **governor.** The President can specify the designation of an administrator; it may be Lieutenant Governor or Chief Commissioner or Administrator. **So, statement I is not correct.**
● The **Parliament can establish a High Court for a Union Territory or put it under the** **jurisdiction of the High Court of an adjacent State.** **So, statement II is correct.**
● The President may make regulations for the peace, progress and good government of the Union territory of-
o (a) the Andaman and Nicobar Islands;
o (b) Lakshadweep;
o (c) Dadra and Nagar Haveli;
o (d) Daman and Diu;
o (e) Puducherry:
● Such a regulation has the effect of law as passed by the Parliament **So, statement III is correct.** **Therefore, option (d) is the correct answer.**
